<subSubSection id="2EDC280E930031AFA9259738982EA1FC" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" type="description">
<paragraph id="2D62466D7B5C63A961941B3246369D91" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BC4D43C4793A68D79A2104AE3C3E9CEB" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
Herb, 4-10 cm tall, terrestrial. Rhizome and roots not seen. Pseudobulb subglobose, 2.5-5 
<normalizedToken id="AE70B96F6BFD4FC1FF766CCB13B60111" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2 mm, enveloped by a basal foliaceous green sheath 1.5 cm long. Leaves not seen. Inflorescence racemose, erect, successively (up to 6) flowered (usually two are open at a time), 7.8 cm. long; peduncle slender, 4 cm long; rachis weakly flexuous, distichous, 3.8 cm long; floral bracts lanceolate. acute, green, 5-7 
<normalizedToken id="31E0D901B032088B9554FB3FE468A7B6" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3 mm. Flowers widely opening, resupinate, fragrance not detected, sepals and petals greenish, labellum rosy brown with a darker median stripe, column greenish suffused with rosy brown, pollinia yellow. Green, 4-6 long ovary with clavate, narrowly winged pedicel. Dorsal sepal oblong-lanceolate, obtuse, erect, 1-veined, 3-5.5 
<normalizedToken id="AED128A6A07A9C127591470F9341478F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.9-1.5 mm. Lateral sepals obliquely oblong-ovate, obtuse, midvein low carinate, parallell to each other under the labellum, 1-veined, 3-5 
<normalizedToken id="01CAEE3910FB2365DC70034CEA8BFC88" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.6-2 mm. Petals linear, obtuse, reflexed, 1-veined, 2.6-5 
<normalizedToken id="7284588C3514824B27621AC1C5C42A85" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-0.6 mm. Labellum subquadrate, distal margin serrate-denticulate, medially with a thickened glossy stripe, 3-5 
<normalizedToken id="FD16A455FF8712D227A227197A616293" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3.5-5 mm; callus bilobed, each side with an erect, subquadrate lobe between which there is a distally thick-walled elliptical cavity. Column semiterete, thick basally but slender above, arcuate on its distal half, apex with small triangular wings on each side, 3 mm long; pollinia four in two pairs, waxy, triangular; anther cap ovoid. Capsule and seeds not seen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D2A368566EBA250E1DC5CD5895A87AB5" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" type="ecology and distribution">
<paragraph id="ACF4037AC701FC4BCF1676E0FC88F689" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Ecology and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="603BF5A37645A8943D73B8197BBA761D" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
<taxonomicName id="F8FA045C128819FCF1F234ABF22BABDA" authorityName="G. A. Romero &amp; Garay" authorityYear="1999" class="Actinopterygii" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Liparis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Liparis aphylla" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aphylla">
<emphasis id="573247182F2217BB2911A0EAC2AC762D" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Liparis aphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in the Andes of Colombia, Ecuador and Peru, within an elevation range of 2600-3300 m. The distribution of this species, based on herbarium records, appears to be highly disjunct (Figure 
<figureCitation id="53B0210C98725FCCA2C6F404D156C6F2" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Known distribution of Liparis aphylla." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.61.7420.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/79788" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">3</figureCitation>
). However, this extreme patchiness may be an artifact of limited collecting, and we suspect that 
<taxonomicName id="C95B33C96859BD8B93DC7DC4489091E8" authorityName="G. A. Romero &amp; Garay" authorityYear="1999" class="Actinopterygii" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Liparis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Liparis aphylla" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aphylla">
<emphasis id="4281E8BE79C030C52796912EA2B1B186" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Liparis aphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
likely occurs throughout the Andean range, at climatically suitable locations ranging from the Cordillera Oriental/East Andes in Colombia to the northern Andes of Peru. Plants of 
<taxonomicName id="7FDF9D808CAAFEC4B54FBAA509E981F0" authorityName="G. A. Romero &amp; Garay" authorityYear="1999" class="Actinopterygii" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Liparis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Liparis aphylla" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aphylla">
<emphasis id="60E627F1F64936C21DA8C3179DBE2F84" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Liparis aphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grow terrestrially among loose moss in wet, cold montane cloud forest with abundant bryophytes. Flowering period: May-July.
</paragraph>
